      when: `When exactly one object needs to coordinate actions across the system — and having more than one instance would cause real problems.

Here's the concrete problem. Your school app has a Logger that writes to a file:

Logger l1 = new Logger(); // opens log file
Logger l2 = new Logger(); // opens the SAME log file again

l1.log("Student logged in");
l2.log("Exam started");

Both are writing to the same file simultaneously. Depending on timing, they overwrite each other, corrupt the output, or lock each other out. You now have two objects fighting over one resource.

The same problem applies to a database connection pool. If two parts of your app each create their own pool, you have double the connections open — most databases have limits, and you'll hit them.

Singleton says: the class itself is responsible for making sure only one instance ever exists. Not the caller — the class.`,
      howItWorks: `There are three pieces.

STEP 1 — Make the constructor private

This is the key move. private constructor means nobody outside the class can call new Logger(). The only way to get an instance is through the class itself:

public class Logger {
    private Logger() {
        // only this class can call this
    }
}

Now this is impossible from outside:
Logger l = new Logger(); // ❌ compile error — constructor is private

STEP 2 — Store the single instance as a static field

static means it belongs to the class, not to any object. There's exactly one copy of it no matter what:

public class Logger {
    private static Logger instance; // starts as null

    private Logger() {}
}

STEP 3 — Provide a public static method to get it

This is the global access point. It creates the instance the first time, then returns the same one every time after:

public class Logger {
    private static Logger instance;

    private Logger() {}

    public static Logger getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new Logger(); // first call — creates it
        }
        return instance; // every call after — returns the same one
    }

    public void log(String message) {
        System.out.println("[LOG] " + message);
    }
}

This is called lazy initialization — the object isn't created until someone actually asks for it.

Usage:

Logger a = Logger.getInstance();
Logger b = Logger.getInstance();

a.log("Student logged in");
b.log("Exam started");

System.out.println(a == b); // true — same object in memory

IMPORTANT — THE THREAD SAFETY TRAP:

The above works fine in single-threaded code. But in a multi-threaded app, two threads could both check instance == null at the same time, both see null, and both create a new instance — breaking the guarantee.

The fix is to use synchronized:

public static synchronized Logger getInstance() {
    if (instance == null) {
        instance = new Logger();
    }
    return instance;
}

synchronized means only one thread can enter this method at a time. Slower, but safe. For most school/bank projects you'll write, this doesn't matter — but it's the trap to know about.`,
