      id: "factory-method",
      name: "Factory Method",
      intent: "Define an interface for creating an object, but let subclasses decide which class to instantiate.",
      analogy: "A school has a training department that produces programmers. But the primary function of the school is to educate, not to produce programmers specifically. The 'factory method' is the school's enrollment process — different departments enroll different types of students.",
      when: `When you have code that needs to create objects, but the exact type depends on something that can change — user config, environment, or a subclass decision — and you want to add new types without editing existing working code.

Here's the problem without it. You're building a school notification system:

class NotificationService {
    public void send(String type, String contact, String message) {
        if (type.equals("email")) {
            System.out.println("Email to " + contact + ": " + message);
        } else if (type.equals("sms")) {
            System.out.println("SMS to " + contact + ": " + message);
        } else if (type.equals("push")) {
            System.out.println("Push to " + contact + ": " + message);
        }
    }
}

Every time you add a new channel — WhatsApp, Slack, in-app — you open NotificationService and edit it. You're modifying code that already works. One typo and the email channel breaks too.

The rule being violated is the Open/Closed Principle: classes should be open for extension, closed for modification. You should be able to add new behavior by adding new code, not by changing old code.

Factory Method fixes this — you add new notification types by adding new classes, not by editing existing ones.`,
      howItWorks: `There are four pieces. Build them one by one.

PIECE 1 — The Product interface

What all created objects have in common. Every notification, regardless of channel, can be sent:

interface Notification {
    void send(String recipient, String message);
}

PIECE 2 — Concrete Products

The actual implementations. Each one knows how to send via its own channel:

class EmailNotification implements Notification {
    @Override
    public void send(String recipient, String message) {
        System.out.println("Email to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

class SMSNotification implements Notification {
    @Override
    public void send(String recipient, String message) {
        System.out.println("SMS to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

PIECE 3 — The Creator (abstract class with the factory method)

This is where the pattern lives. The factory method is declared here but not implemented — subclasses decide that. The business logic lives here too, and it only talks to the Notification interface — never to EmailNotification or SMSNotification directly:

abstract class NotificationService {
    // The factory method — subclasses override this one line
    public abstract Notification createNotification(String contact);

    // Business logic — uses whatever the factory method returns
    public void notifyStudent(String contact, String message) {
        Notification n = createNotification(contact); // ← factory method
        n.send(contact, message);
        // never says: new EmailNotification() or new SMSNotification()
        // it doesn't know and doesn't care which type it got
    }
}

That last point is the whole idea. notifyStudent contains the real work — logging, error handling, retries, whatever. It never changes, no matter how many new channels you add. Only createNotification changes — and only in subclasses.

PIECE 4 — Concrete Creators

Each subclass overrides the factory method and decides what to create:

class EmailService extends NotificationService {
    @Override
    public Notification createNotification(String contact) {
        return new EmailNotification(); // this subclass creates Email
    }
}

class SMSService extends NotificationService {
    @Override
    public Notification createNotification(String contact) {
        return new SMSNotification(); // this subclass creates SMS
    }
}

Usage:

NotificationService service = new EmailService();
service.notifyStudent("ali@school.com", "Exam on Monday!"); // Email

service = new SMSService();
service.notifyStudent("+880123", "Exam on Monday!"); // SMS

ADDING WHATSAPP — zero changes to existing code:

class WhatsAppNotification implements Notification { // new product
    @Override
    public void send(String recipient, String message) {
        System.out.println("WhatsApp to " + recipient + ": " + message);
    }
}

class WhatsAppService extends NotificationService { // new creator
    @Override
    public Notification createNotification(String contact) {
        return new WhatsAppNotification();
    }
}

EmailService, SMSService, NotificationService — all untouched. This is Open/Closed in action.`,
