      id: "abstract-factory",
      name: "Abstract Factory",
      intent: "Provide an interface for creating families of related or dependent objects without specifying their concrete classes.",
      analogy: "Imagine a furniture shop with two styles: Modern and Victorian. You need a Chair, Sofa, and Coffee Table in each style. Customers get mad when they receive non-matching furniture. An Abstract Factory ensures that when you pick 'Modern', everything you get is Modern.",
      when: `When you need to create families of related objects that must be used together — and mixing objects from different families would break things or produce inconsistent results.

Here's the concrete problem. Your school app has two UI themes: Classic and Modern. Each theme has its own Button and TextBox. Without Abstract Factory, the client creates them directly:

class LoginPage {
    void render() {
        ClassicButton btn = new ClassicButton();   // hardcoded Classic
        ModernTextBox  tb  = new ModernTextBox();  // accidentally Modern
        // Classic button + Modern textbox = broken UI
    }
}

Nothing stops a developer from mixing a Classic button with a Modern textbox. No compiler error. Just a visually broken, inconsistent page. The more components you add — dropdowns, checkboxes, tables — the worse the problem gets.

Abstract Factory fixes this by making the family the unit of selection. You pick one factory, and everything you get from it is guaranteed to belong to the same family.`,
      howItWorks: `There are four pieces.

PIECE 1 — Abstract Product interfaces

One interface per product type. Not per variant — per type:

interface Button  { void render(); }
interface TextBox { void render(); }

You now have two product types. Each will have multiple variants (Classic, Modern).

PIECE 2 — Concrete Products (the variants)

Classic family:

class ClassicButton implements Button {
    @Override public void render() {
        System.out.println("[Classic Button: sharp corners, serif font]");
    }
}
class ClassicTextBox implements TextBox {
    @Override public void render() {
        System.out.println("[Classic TextBox: underline only]");
    }
}

Modern family:

class ModernButton implements Button {
    @Override public void render() {
        System.out.println("[Modern Button: rounded, shadow]");
    }
}
class ModernTextBox implements TextBox {
    @Override public void render() {
        System.out.println("[Modern TextBox: filled, floating label]");
    }
}

PIECE 3 — The Abstract Factory interface

One method per product type. Each method returns an abstract type — never a concrete one:

interface UIFactory {
    Button  createButton();
    TextBox createTextBox();
}

PIECE 4 — Concrete Factories (one per family)

Each factory only creates its own family. ClassicUIFactory can only produce Classic things — it's impossible to get a Modern object out of it:

class ClassicUIFactory implements UIFactory {
    @Override public Button  createButton()  { return new ClassicButton();  }
    @Override public TextBox createTextBox() { return new ClassicTextBox(); }
}

class ModernUIFactory implements UIFactory {
    @Override public Button  createButton()  { return new ModernButton();  }
    @Override public TextBox createTextBox() { return new ModernTextBox(); }
}

THE CLIENT — never mentions concrete classes:

class LoginPage {
    private Button  btn;
    private TextBox tb;

    public LoginPage(UIFactory factory) {
        btn = factory.createButton();   // whatever family the factory belongs to
        tb  = factory.createTextBox();  // same family, guaranteed
    }

    public void render() { tb.render(); btn.render(); }
}

Usage — swap the entire family by changing one line:

LoginPage classic = new LoginPage(new ClassicUIFactory());
classic.render();
// [Classic TextBox: underline only]
// [Classic Button: sharp corners, serif font]

LoginPage modern = new LoginPage(new ModernUIFactory());
modern.render();
// [Modern TextBox: filled, floating label]
// [Modern Button: rounded, shadow]

The key difference from Factory Method: Factory Method creates one product. Abstract Factory creates a whole family of related products and ensures they're always used together.

THE ONE TRADEOFF TO KNOW:
Adding a new product type (say, Dropdown) requires adding createDropdown() to the UIFactory interface — which means updating every concrete factory. Adding a new family (say, DarkTheme) is easy — just add one new factory class. So: new families = easy. New product types = work.`,
