      id: "builder",
      name: "Builder",
      intent: "Separate the construction of a complex object from its representation so the same construction process can create different results.",
      analogy: "To build a simple house you need: walls, a floor, a door, windows, a roof. But to build a luxury house you also need: a pool, a garage, smart lighting. A Builder lets you use the same construction steps but skip or add steps as needed — without a constructor that takes 15 parameters.",
      when: `When constructing an object requires many fields — especially when some are optional — and passing them all through a constructor becomes unreadable and error-prone.

Here's the concrete problem. A student enrollment has required fields (name, grade) and optional ones (sport, scholarship, hostel, bus route, locker number). You add them all to the constructor:

class Student {
    public Student(String name, int grade, String sport,
                   boolean scholarship, boolean hostel,
                   String busRoute, int lockerNumber) { ... }
}

Now to create a simple student with no extras:

Student s = new Student("Afif", 10, null, false, false, null, 0);

What does false mean here? Which false — scholarship or hostel? What's the 0? You have to look up the constructor every single time. And if you accidentally swap the two booleans, nothing breaks at compile time — you just get silently wrong data.

This is called the telescoping constructor problem. Builder solves it by letting you set only what you need, with named steps, in any order.`,
      howItWorks: `There are three pieces.

PIECE 1 — The target class with a private constructor

The object you're building. Its constructor is private — nobody can call new Student() directly. The only way to create one is through the Builder:

class Student {
    private final String name;   // required
    private final int grade;     // required
    private final String sport;
    private final boolean scholarship;
    private final boolean hostel;

    private Student(Builder builder) {
        this.name        = builder.name;
        this.grade       = builder.grade;
        this.sport       = builder.sport;
        this.scholarship = builder.scholarship;
        this.hostel      = builder.hostel;
    }
}

PIECE 2 — The inner Builder class

Lives inside Student. Holds the same fields with sensible defaults for optional ones:

public static class Builder {
    // required — no defaults
    private final String name;
    private final int grade;

    // optional — default values
    private String  sport       = "None";
    private boolean scholarship = false;
    private boolean hostel      = false;

    // Required fields go in the Builder constructor
    public Builder(String name, int grade) {
        this.name  = name;
        this.grade = grade;
    }

    // Each optional field gets a setter that returns this — so you can chain
    public Builder sport(String s)        { this.sport = s;        return this; }
    public Builder scholarship(boolean b) { this.scholarship = b;  return this; }
    public Builder hostel(boolean b)      { this.hostel = b;       return this; }

    // build() calls the private constructor
    public Student build() {
        return new Student(this);
    }
}

PIECE 3 — Usage

Required fields go in the Builder constructor. Optional fields are chained. You only set what you need:

// Simple student — no extras
Student s1 = new Student.Builder("Afif", 10).build();

// Student with extras — only the ones that apply
Student s2 = new Student.Builder("Sadia", 11)
    .sport("Football")
    .scholarship(true)
    .hostel(true)
    .build();

Compare to the telescoping constructor version:
new Student("Sadia", 11, "Football", true, true, null, 0)
// which boolean is which? what's the null? what's the 0?

The Builder version reads like a sentence. The constructor version requires you to memorize parameter order.

WHY return this IN EACH SETTER?

sport() returns the Builder itself — not void, not Student. That's what allows chaining:

.sport("Football")       // returns Builder
.scholarship(true)       // called on that Builder, returns Builder again
.hostel(true)            // same
.build()                 // finally called on Builder, returns Student

If sport() returned void, you couldn't chain — you'd have to write separate lines for each setter.`,
