      id: "prototype",
      name: "Prototype",
      intent: "Specify the kinds of objects to create using a prototypical instance, and create new objects by copying (cloning) that prototype.",
      analogy: "In biology, a cell reproduces by copying itself through division. The copy starts as an exact duplicate, then develops its own identity. You don't design a new cell from scratch — you clone the existing one.",
      when: `When object creation is expensive — meaning the constructor does heavy work like database calls, file reads, network requests, or complex calculations that take real time.

Here's a concrete example. You have a User class whose constructor talks to a database to fetch permissions:

public class User {
    String name;
    List<String> permissions;

    public User(String role) {
        // Talks to a real database — takes ~200ms every time
        this.permissions = Database.fetchPermissions(role);
    }
}

Now you create 3 admin users:

User a = new User("ADMIN"); // 200ms — DB call
User b = new User("ADMIN"); // 200ms — DB call again
User c = new User("ADMIN"); // 200ms — DB call again
// Total: 600ms — for identical data

The permissions for "ADMIN" are the same every time. You're hitting the database 3 times for the exact same result.

With Prototype, you pay the cost once and clone the rest:

User template = new User("ADMIN"); // 200ms — one DB call

User a = template.clone(); a.name = "Alice"; // instant — no DB
User b = template.clone(); b.name = "Bob";   // instant — no DB
User c = template.clone(); c.name = "Eve";   // instant — no DB
// Total: 200ms — no matter how many users you create

The expensive part isn't making the object — it's the work that happens inside the constructor. Prototype lets you do that work once and reuse the result.`,
      howItWorks: `First, the most common mistake. This is NOT a clone:

User a = template; // same object, same memory address
a.name = "Alice";  // changes template too 💥

You need an actual independent copy in memory. That's what clone() is for.

Java has a built-in clone() method inside every object, but it's locked behind two things.

STEP 1 — Declare your class is okay to be cloned:

public class User implements Cloneable { // just a flag — unlocks cloning
    String name;
    List<String> permissions;
}

Cloneable is just a marker interface — it has no methods. It simply tells Java "this class permits cloning." Without it, calling clone() throws a CloneNotSupportedException.

STEP 2 — Override clone() and make it public:

@Override
public User clone() {
    try {
        User copy = (User) super.clone(); // Java's built-in — copies all fields, skips constructor
        copy.permissions = new ArrayList<>(this.permissions); // we fix the List problem
        return copy;
    } catch (CloneNotSupportedException e) {
        throw new RuntimeException(e);
    }
}

Java's built-in clone() is protected — meaning nobody outside the class can call it. So we override it and make it public so the rest of your code can actually use it.

Inside, we call super.clone() — that's Java doing the real work. It creates a new object in memory and copies all field values without running the constructor. That's the crucial part — skipping the constructor means skipping the DB call.

THE SHALLOW COPY TRAP:

But super.clone() has one problem. For a List, it copies the memory address, not the actual list contents:

// After super.clone() alone:
template.permissions ──┐
                        ├──▶ ["READ", "WRITE"]  // same list, shared memory
copy.permissions     ──┘

copy.permissions.add("DELETE"); // accidentally modifies template too 💥

So we fix it manually by making a fresh list:

copy.permissions = new ArrayList<>(this.permissions); // now truly independent

After this:

template.permissions ──▶ ["READ", "WRITE"]  // untouched ✅
copy.permissions     ──▶ ["READ", "WRITE"]  // independent copy ✅

Summary: We write clone(), Java does the heavy lifting inside super.clone(), and we patch the one problem it leaves behind. The constructor never runs, the DB is never hit, and each copy is fully independent.`,
      alternatives: `super.clone() is not the only way. There are three alternatives, each with a different tradeoff.

1. COPY CONSTRUCTOR

A second constructor that accepts an existing object and copies its fields — no DB call involved:

public class User {
    String name;
    String role;
    List<String> permissions;

    // Original constructor — hits DB, expensive
    public User(String role) {
        this.role        = role;
        this.permissions = Database.fetchPermissions(role); // 200ms DB call
    }

    // Copy constructor — no DB call, just copies fields
    public User(User source) {
        this.role        = source.role;
        this.name        = source.name;
        this.permissions = new ArrayList<>(source.permissions); // fresh list, safe
    }

    @Override
    public User clone() {
        return new User(this); // calls copy constructor, not the original one
    }
}

When new User(this) runs, Java looks for a constructor that accepts a User object — it finds the copy constructor, not the original one. The DB never gets touched again. This is the approach recommended in Effective Java by Joshua Bloch — preferred over super.clone() for most situations because it's explicit, readable, and doesn't inherit Java's cloning baggage.

2. MANUAL FIELD-BY-FIELD COPY

No special mechanism at all — you just manually set every field yourself:

public class User {
    String name;
    String role;
    List<String> permissions;

    public User(String role) {
        this.role        = role;
        this.permissions = Database.fetchPermissions(role); // 200ms DB call
    }

    // Extra empty constructor — so new User() doesn't trigger the DB call
    public User() {}

    public User copy() {
        User newUser        = new User(); // empty object, no DB call
        newUser.role        = this.role;
        newUser.name        = this.name;
        newUser.permissions = new ArrayList<>(this.permissions); // fresh list
        return newUser;
    }
}

Most control, most verbose. The risk: if your class gains a new field later and you forget to add it here, the copy silently comes out incomplete — no compiler warning, no error, just wrong data at runtime. Rarely used in production for this reason.

3. SERIALIZATION

Convert the entire object into bytes, then convert those bytes back into a new object. Java handles all the copying automatically — you don't manually copy any field:

public class User implements Serializable {
    String name;
    String role;
    List<String> permissions;

    public User(String role) {
        this.role        = role;
        this.permissions = Database.fetchPermissions(role); // 200ms DB call
    }

    public User deepCopy() {
        try {
            ByteArrayOutputStream bos = new ByteArrayOutputStream();
            new ObjectOutputStream(bos).writeObject(this);
            return (User) new ObjectInputStream(
                new ByteArrayInputStream(bos.toByteArray())
            ).readObject();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            throw new RuntimeException(e);
        }
    }
}

No field manually copied — Java serializes everything automatically, including nested Lists, Maps, and objects inside objects. The trap: every class in the object graph must implement Serializable — if any nested object doesn't, it throws at runtime with no compile-time warning. Also slower than the other approaches and overkill for simple objects.

WHICH TO PICK?
• Simple fields only             → Copy constructor
• Has Lists/Maps                 → Copy constructor + new ArrayList<>()
• Deeply nested objects          → Serialization
• Need full control every field  → Manual copy

In real Java codebases, the copy constructor is the most common. It's clean, readable, no boilerplate, and handles most situations well.`,
