      when: `When you have an existing class that does exactly what you need — but its method names and signatures don't match what your code expects, and you can't change either side.

Here's the concrete problem. Your new school reporting system expects grades as percentages:

interface GradeProvider {
    double getPercentage(String studentId);
}

But you have a legacy grading system from 5 years ago that returns letter grades:

class LegacyGradeSystem {
    public String getLetterGrade(String studentId) { ... }
}

You can't change LegacyGradeSystem — other parts of the school still use it. You can't change your new ReportCard — it's already built around GradeProvider. The two sides speak different languages.

You need a translator that sits between them. That's the Adapter.`,
      howItWorks: `There are three pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Target interface (what your code expects)

This is the interface your new system is built around. It doesn't know or care about the legacy system:

interface GradeProvider {
    double getPercentage(String studentId);
}

PIECE 2 — The Adaptee (the existing class you can't change)

This already works correctly — it just speaks the wrong language:

class LegacyGradeSystem {
    public String getLetterGrade(String studentId) {
        if (studentId.equals("S001")) return "A";
        if (studentId.equals("S002")) return "B";
        return "C";
    }
}

PIECE 3 — The Adapter (the translator)

Implements the target interface so your new code can use it, but internally delegates to the legacy system:

class GradeAdapter implements GradeProvider {
    private LegacyGradeSystem legacy;

    public GradeAdapter(LegacyGradeSystem legacy) {
        this.legacy = legacy;
    }

    @Override
    public double getPercentage(String studentId) {
        // calls old method → translates result → returns in new format
        String letter = legacy.getLetterGrade(studentId);
        switch (letter) {
            case "A": return 90.0;
            case "B": return 75.0;
            default:  return 60.0;
        }
    }
}

Usage — your ReportCard only knows about GradeProvider. It never sees LegacyGradeSystem:

LegacyGradeSystem old     = new LegacyGradeSystem();
GradeProvider     adapted = new GradeAdapter(old);
ReportCard        card    = new ReportCard(adapted);

card.generate("S001"); // → 90.0%
card.generate("S002"); // → 75.0%

The three sides of this pattern:
• Your new code  → talks to GradeProvider (target interface)
• GradeAdapter   → implements GradeProvider, wraps LegacyGradeSystem
• LegacyGradeSystem → never touched, never changed

If tomorrow you switch from LegacyGradeSystem to a new DatabaseGradeSystem, you write one new Adapter class. ReportCard doesn't change at all.`,
