      id: "bridge",
      name: "Bridge",
      intent: "Decouple an abstraction from its implementation so the two can vary independently.",
      analogy: "A TV remote (abstraction) and the TV (implementation). The remote works with any TV. You can swap the remote or swap the TV without affecting the other. Bridge is like replacing the cable between them with a standard plug — both sides evolve independently.",
      when: `When you have two independent dimensions of variation, and combining them through inheritance creates a class explosion.

Here's the concrete problem. You have shapes: Circle and Square. You also have renderers: Vector and Raster. You start with inheritance:

class VectorCircle  extends Shape { ... }
class RasterCircle  extends Shape { ... }
class VectorSquare  extends Shape { ... }
class RasterSquare  extends Shape { ... }
// 4 classes for 2 shapes × 2 renderers

Now add Triangle and SVGRenderer:

class VectorTriangle  extends Shape { ... }
class RasterTriangle  extends Shape { ... }
class SVGCircle       extends Shape { ... }
class SVGSquare       extends Shape { ... }
class SVGTriangle     extends Shape { ... }
// 9 classes for 3 shapes × 3 renderers

The formula is: N shapes × M renderers = N×M classes. Every time you add one shape, you add M classes. Every time you add one renderer, you add N classes. This is called a class explosion.

Bridge says: shapes and renderers are two separate things. Keep them in two separate hierarchies and connect them with a reference — the "bridge". Then it's N + M classes instead of N × M.`,
      howItWorks: `There are four pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Implementation interface (one dimension)

This is the renderer side. Defines what renderers can do:

interface Renderer {
    void renderCircle(double radius);
    void renderSquare(double side);
}

PIECE 2 — Concrete Implementations

class VectorRenderer implements Renderer {
    @Override public void renderCircle(double r) {
        System.out.println("Vector circle, radius=" + r);
    }
    @Override public void renderSquare(double s) {
        System.out.println("Vector square, side=" + s);
    }
}

class RasterRenderer implements Renderer {
    @Override public void renderCircle(double r) {
        System.out.println("Raster circle: " + (int)(Math.PI*r*r) + " pixels");
    }
    @Override public void renderSquare(double s) {
        System.out.println("Raster square: " + (int)(s*s) + " pixels");
    }
}

PIECE 3 — The Abstraction (other dimension) — holds a reference to the implementation

This is the bridge. Shape holds a Renderer reference. It doesn't inherit from Renderer — it has one:

abstract class Shape {
    protected Renderer renderer; // ← the bridge

    public Shape(Renderer renderer) {
        this.renderer = renderer;
    }

    public abstract void draw();
}

protected means subclasses (Circle, Square) can access this.renderer directly.

PIECE 4 — Concrete Abstractions

class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;

    public Circle(Renderer renderer, double radius) {
        super(renderer); // passes renderer to Shape
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        renderer.renderCircle(radius); // delegates to whichever renderer was injected
    }
}

class Square extends Shape {
    private double side;

    public Square(Renderer renderer, double side) {
        super(renderer);
        this.side = side;
    }

    @Override
    public void draw() {
        renderer.renderSquare(side);
    }
}

Usage — mix and match freely:

Shape c1 = new Circle(new VectorRenderer(), 5);
Shape c2 = new Circle(new RasterRenderer(), 5);
Shape s1 = new Square(new VectorRenderer(), 4);

c1.draw(); // Vector circle, radius=5
c2.draw(); // Raster circle: 78 pixels
s1.draw(); // Vector square, side=4

Adding SVGRenderer? One new class. Circle and Square automatically work with it.
Adding Triangle? One new class. VectorRenderer and RasterRenderer automatically work with it.
Total classes: shapes + renderers, not shapes × renderers.`,
