      id: "composite",
      name: "Composite",
      intent: "Compose objects into tree structures to represent part-whole hierarchies. Lets clients treat individual objects and compositions uniformly.",
      analogy: "A military hierarchy: an army has divisions, divisions have brigades, brigades have platoons, platoons have soldiers. You can give an order to the entire army or a single soldier using the same 'execute order' command.",
      when: `When you have a tree-like structure where individual items and groups of items should be treated the same way by the calling code.

Here's the concrete problem. A school has teachers. A school also has departments that contain teachers. And the school itself contains departments. You want to ask any of them: "what's your total salary cost?"

Without Composite, you write different code for each level:

class Teacher    { double getSalary() { ... } }
class Department { double getSalaryBill() { ... } } // different method name
class School     { double getTotalBill() { ... } }  // another different name

// To print the whole tree, you need separate logic for each level:
System.out.println(teacher.getSalary());
System.out.println(department.getSalaryBill());
System.out.println(school.getTotalBill());

And if you want sub-departments inside departments? You add yet another class and yet more special-case code. The tree structure forces you to handle every level differently.

Composite says: make a Teacher and a Department implement the same interface. Then a Department can contain both Teachers and other Departments — and you call getMonthlySalary() on anything, at any level, uniformly.`,
      howItWorks: `There are three pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Component interface (common interface for everything)

Both leaves and composites implement this:

interface SchoolMember {
    String getName();
    double getMonthlySalary();
    void print(String indent);
}

PIECE 2 — The Leaf (individual, no children)

A Teacher is a leaf — it has a salary, it can't contain other members:

class Teacher implements SchoolMember {
    private String name;
    private double salary;

    public Teacher(String name, double salary) {
        this.name = name; this.salary = salary;
    }

    @Override public String getName()           { return name; }
    @Override public double getMonthlySalary()  { return salary; }
    @Override public void print(String indent) {
        System.out.println(indent + "Teacher: " + name + " ($" + salary + ")");
    }
}

PIECE 3 — The Composite (container, has children)

A Department implements the same interface as Teacher, but also holds a list of children — which can be Teachers or other Departments:

class Department implements SchoolMember {
    private String name;
    private List<SchoolMember> members = new ArrayList<>();

    public Department(String name) { this.name = name; }

    public void add(SchoolMember m)    { members.add(m); }
    public void remove(SchoolMember m) { members.remove(m); }

    @Override public String getName() { return name; }

    @Override
    public double getMonthlySalary() {
        // Recursively sums all children — Teachers return their salary,
        // sub-Departments sum their own children, and so on
        return members.stream()
            .mapToDouble(SchoolMember::getMonthlySalary)
            .sum();
    }

    @Override
    public void print(String indent) {
        System.out.println(indent + "Dept: " + name
            + " (total: $" + getMonthlySalary() + ")");
        for (SchoolMember m : members) {
            m.print(indent + "  "); // each child indents further
        }
    }
}

Usage — the client code calls the same methods regardless of what it's holding:

Department science = new Department("Science");
science.add(new Teacher("Mr. Karim", 3000));
science.add(new Teacher("Ms. Rina",  2800));

Department school = new Department("School");
school.add(science);
school.add(new Teacher("Principal", 5000));

school.print("");
// Dept: School (total: $10800)
//   Dept: Science (total: $5800)
//     Teacher: Mr. Karim ($3000)
//     Teacher: Ms. Rina ($2800)
//   Teacher: Principal ($5000)

school.getMonthlySalary(); // 10800 — same call on any level

The client never checks "is this a Teacher or a Department?" It just calls getMonthlySalary() and the right thing happens recursively.`,
