      name: "Facade",
      intent: "Provide a simplified interface to a complex subsystem.",
      analogy: "Calling a bank's customer service. You say 'I want to open an account.' The agent (facade) handles identity verification, credit check, account number generation, and welcome kit — you just give your name.",
      when: `When a client needs to interact with several subsystem classes in a specific sequence, and that coordination logic shouldn't be the client's responsibility — especially when many different clients would otherwise duplicate that coordination.

Here's the concrete problem. To admit a student, the caller must:

FormValidator validator = new FormValidator();
FeeProcessor feeProcessor = new FeeProcessor();
ClassAssigner classAssigner = new ClassAssigner();
IDCardGenerator idGenerator = new IDCardGenerator();

if (!validator.validate(name, age)) return;
if (!feeProcessor.processPayment(fee)) return;
int grade = classAssigner.assignClass(age);
String id = idGenerator.generate(name, grade);

Every part of the app that admits students — the front desk, the online portal, the admin panel — duplicates this entire sequence. If the sequence changes (say, you add a medical check step), you update every caller.

The client knows too much: it knows about FormValidator, FeeProcessor, ClassAssigner, and IDCardGenerator. It knows the exact order. It handles every failure case. That's not the client's job.

Facade wraps the whole sequence behind one method. The client says admitStudent(name, age, fee) and gets back a student ID.`,
      howItWorks: `There are two pieces — the subsystem and the facade.

PIECE 1 — The subsystem classes (complex internals)

These already exist and work correctly. They don't know about each other:

class FormValidator {
    public boolean validate(String name, int age) {
        System.out.println("Validating: " + name + " age " + age);
        return age >= 5 && !name.isEmpty();
    }
}

class FeeProcessor {
    public boolean processPayment(double amount) {
        System.out.printf("Processing fee: $%.2f%n", amount);
        return true;
    }
}

class ClassAssigner {
    public int assignClass(int age) {
        return Math.max(1, Math.min(12, age - 5));
    }
}

class IDCardGenerator {
    public String generate(String name, int grade) {
        return "SCH-" + name.substring(0,2).toUpperCase() + "-G" + grade;
    }
}

PIECE 2 — The Facade

Holds references to all subsystem classes. Exposes one simple method. Handles the sequence and failures internally:

class AdmissionFacade {
    private FormValidator  validator  = new FormValidator();
    private FeeProcessor   fee        = new FeeProcessor();
    private ClassAssigner  assigner   = new ClassAssigner();
    private IDCardGenerator generator = new IDCardGenerator();

    public String admitStudent(String name, int age, double feeAmount) {
        if (!validator.validate(name, age))       return null; // step 1
        if (!fee.processPayment(feeAmount))        return null; // step 2
        int grade    = assigner.assignClass(age);              // step 3
        return generator.generate(name, grade);                // step 4
    }
}

Usage:

AdmissionFacade admission = new AdmissionFacade();
String id = admission.admitStudent("Afif", 15, 500.0);
System.out.println("Student ID: " + id);

The client knows nothing about FormValidator, FeeProcessor, or the sequence. If you add a medical check step tomorrow, you update AdmissionFacade only — all callers are automatically updated.

IMPORTANT — Facade doesn't prevent direct access:
Facade is not a lock. Developers can still call FormValidator directly if they need to. Facade just provides a simpler path for the common case. This is different from Proxy, which controls access — Facade only simplifies it.`,
