      when: `When one object changes state and multiple other objects need to react to that change — but you don't want the changing object to know who those others are or how many there are.

Here's the concrete problem. A bank account balance changes. Three services need to react:
• EmailAlert sends a notification
• FraudDetection checks for suspicious activity
• SavingsAdvisor suggests investments if balance is high

Without Observer:

class BankAccount {
    private EmailAlert email = new EmailAlert();
    private FraudDetection fraud = new FraudDetection();
    private SavingsAdvisor advisor = new SavingsAdvisor();

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        balance += amount;
        email.notify(accountId, balance);   // direct call
        fraud.check(accountId, amount);     // direct call
        advisor.advise(accountId, balance); // direct call
    }
}

BankAccount now knows about EmailAlert, FraudDetection, and SavingsAdvisor. It imports them, depends on them, and calls them directly. To add a new service (SMSAlert), you edit BankAccount. To remove FraudDetection, you edit BankAccount. The account class has nothing to do with fraud detection — it's a bank account, not a notification hub.

Observer decouples this: BankAccount announces "I changed." Anyone who cares subscribes and reacts. BankAccount doesn't know who subscribed.`,
      howItWorks: `There are four pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Observer interface

What every subscriber must implement. One method — the notification:

interface AccountObserver {
    void onBalanceChange(String accountId, double newBalance, double change);
}

PIECE 2 — The Subject (the object being watched)

Maintains a list of observers. Notifies them all when something changes. Crucially, it only knows about the Observer interface — not about EmailAlert or FraudDetection specifically:

class BankAccount {
    private String accountId;
    private double balance;
    private List<AccountObserver> observers = new ArrayList<>();

    public void addObserver(AccountObserver o)    { observers.add(o); }
    public void removeObserver(AccountObserver o) { observers.remove(o); }

    public void deposit(double amount) {
        balance += amount;
        notifyAll(amount); // ← one call, all observers react
    }

    private void notifyAll(double change) {
        for (AccountObserver o : observers) {
            o.onBalanceChange(accountId, balance, change);
        }
    }
}

PIECE 3 — Concrete Observers

Each one knows how to react. They implement AccountObserver and nothing else:

class EmailAlertService implements AccountObserver {
    @Override
    public void onBalanceChange(String accountId, double newBalance, double change) {
        System.out.printf("[EMAIL] Account %s changed by $%.2f. New balance: $%.2f%n",
            accountId, change, newBalance);
    }
}

class FraudDetectionService implements AccountObserver {
    @Override
    public void onBalanceChange(String accountId, double newBalance, double change) {
        if (change < -5000) {
            System.out.println("[FRAUD] Large withdrawal on " + accountId + "!");
        }
    }
}

PIECE 4 — Wiring (subscribe at runtime)

BankAccount account = new BankAccount("ACC-001", 8000);
account.addObserver(new EmailAlertService());
account.addObserver(new FraudDetectionService());

account.deposit(3000);
// [EMAIL] Account ACC-001 changed by $3000. New balance: $11000
// (fraud check runs — no alert since it's a deposit)

account.removeObserver(emailAlert); // unsubscribe — email stops, nothing else changes

To add SMSAlert: create class SMSAlertService implements AccountObserver, call account.addObserver(new SMSAlertService()). BankAccount never changes.

PUSH vs PULL:
The example above uses push — the subject sends all the data (accountId, newBalance, change) in the notification. An alternative is pull — send just a signal, and each observer fetches what it needs from the subject. Push is simpler. Pull gives observers more control over what they fetch.`,
