      when: `When an object can be in several distinct states, and its behavior changes significantly based on which state it's in — especially when you find yourself writing large if/else or switch blocks that check the current state before every operation.

Here's the concrete problem. A library book can be Available, CheckedOut, or Reserved. Without State:

class Book {
    private String state = "available";

    public void checkout(String student) {
        if (state.equals("available")) {
            state = "checkedout";
            System.out.println("Checked out to " + student);
        } else if (state.equals("checkedout")) {
            System.out.println("Already checked out");
        } else if (state.equals("reserved")) {
            if (student.equals(reservedFor)) {
                state = "checkedout";
            } else {
                System.out.println("Reserved for someone else");
            }
        }
    }

    public void returnBook() {
        if (state.equals("checkedout")) { state = "available"; }
        else { System.out.println("Not checked out"); }
    }

    public void reserve(String student) {
        if (state.equals("available")) { state = "reserved"; }
        else { System.out.println("Cannot reserve"); }
    }
}

Every method is a pile of if/else. Adding a new state (say "UnderRepair") means editing every single method — checkout, return, reserve — to add a new branch. These methods grow together, and a bug in one state's logic sits right next to the logic for all other states.

State says: give each state its own class. Each state class only contains the logic for that state. The book delegates to whichever state object is currently active.`,
      howItWorks: `There are three pieces.

PIECE 1 — The State interface

Every state must handle the same set of operations. If an operation is invalid in a given state, that state class just prints an error — it doesn't do nothing silently:

interface BookState {
    void checkout(BookContext book, String student);
    void returnBook(BookContext book);
    void reserve(BookContext book, String student);
    String getStateName();
}

PIECE 2 — The Context (the Book)

Holds a reference to the current state object. All operations delegate to it:

class BookContext {
    private BookState state;
    private String title;
    private String holder;

    public BookContext(String title) {
        this.title = title;
        this.state = new AvailableState(); // starts available
    }

    // State classes call this to transition
    public void setState(BookState s) { this.state = s; }
    public void setHolder(String h)   { this.holder = h; }
    public String getHolder()         { return holder; }

    // Operations just delegate — no if/else here
    public void checkout(String student) { state.checkout(this, student); }
    public void returnBook()             { state.returnBook(this); }
    public void reserve(String student)  { state.reserve(this, student); }
}

PIECE 3 — Concrete State classes

Each one handles all operations for that state, and triggers transitions by calling book.setState():

class AvailableState implements BookState {
    @Override
    public void checkout(BookContext book, String student) {
        book.setHolder(student);
        book.setState(new CheckedOutState()); // transition
        System.out.println("Checked out to " + student);
    }
    @Override
    public void returnBook(BookContext book) {
        System.out.println("Error: book is already available");
    }
    @Override
    public void reserve(BookContext book, String student) {
        book.setHolder(student);
        book.setState(new ReservedState()); // transition
        System.out.println("Reserved for " + student);
    }
    @Override public String getStateName() { return "Available"; }
}

class CheckedOutState implements BookState {
    @Override
    public void checkout(BookContext book, String student) {
        System.out.println("Error: already checked out by " + book.getHolder());
    }
    @Override
    public void returnBook(BookContext book) {
        System.out.println(book.getHolder() + " returned the book");
        book.setHolder(null);
        book.setState(new AvailableState()); // transition back
    }
    @Override
    public void reserve(BookContext book, String student) {
        System.out.println("Error: cannot reserve a checked-out book");
    }
    @Override public String getStateName() { return "Checked Out"; }
}

Usage:

BookContext book = new BookContext("Clean Code");
book.checkout("Afif");    // Checked out to Afif
book.checkout("Sadia");   // Error: already checked out by Afif
book.returnBook();        // Afif returned the book
book.reserve("Karim");    // Reserved for Karim

Adding "UnderRepair" state: write one new class UnderRepairState. No existing state class changes.

THE KEY INSIGHT — state transitions happen inside state classes:
AvailableState knows "after checkout, I become CheckedOut." CheckedOutState knows "after return, I become Available." The Context (Book) never decides transitions — states decide for themselves. This keeps each state class fully self-contained.`,
