      when: `When a request might be handled by one of several objects, and you want to decide at runtime which one handles it — without the sender knowing who that is.

Here's the concrete problem. A bank needs approval for transactions based on amount. Without Chain of Responsibility:

class TransactionApprover {
    public void approve(String txId, double amount) {
        if (amount <= 1000) {
            System.out.println("Teller approved " + txId);
        } else if (amount <= 10000) {
            System.out.println("Manager approved " + txId);
        } else if (amount <= 100000) {
            System.out.println("Director approved " + txId);
        } else {
            System.out.println("CEO approved " + txId);
        }
    }
}

To add a new approval level (say, Regional Manager between Manager and Director), you edit this class, find the right if/else position, and insert a new branch. You're modifying working code. The approval levels — Teller, Manager, Director, CEO — are permanently baked into one class. You can't reorder them, skip one, or build a different chain for a different branch.

Chain of Responsibility links handlers together like a chain. Each handler either processes the request or passes it to the next one. The sender just sends to the first handler in the chain and forgets about it.`,
      howItWorks: `There are three pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Handler base class

Each handler has one job: handle if it can, otherwise pass to next. The setNext() method returns the next handler so you can chain them in one line:

abstract class ApprovalHandler {
    protected ApprovalHandler next; // link to the next handler

    public ApprovalHandler setNext(ApprovalHandler next) {
        this.next = next;
        return next; // return next so you can chain: a.setNext(b).setNext(c)
    }

    public abstract void approve(String txId, double amount);

    // Helper: pass to next, or report no handler
    protected void passToNext(String txId, double amount) {
        if (next != null) {
            next.approve(txId, amount);
        } else {
            System.out.println("No handler for $" + amount + " — request dropped");
        }
    }
}

PIECE 2 — Concrete Handlers

Each one handles what's within its limit and passes the rest:

class Teller extends ApprovalHandler {
    @Override
    public void approve(String txId, double amount) {
        if (amount <= 1000) {
            System.out.println("[Teller] Approved " + txId + " for $" + amount);
        } else {
            System.out.println("[Teller] $" + amount + " exceeds my limit — escalating...");
            passToNext(txId, amount);
        }
    }
}

class Manager extends ApprovalHandler {
    @Override
    public void approve(String txId, double amount) {
        if (amount <= 10000) {
            System.out.println("[Manager] Approved " + txId + " for $" + amount);
        } else {
            System.out.println("[Manager] Escalating...");
            passToNext(txId, amount);
        }
    }
}

class Director extends ApprovalHandler {
    @Override
    public void approve(String txId, double amount) {
        if (amount <= 100000) {
            System.out.println("[Director] Approved " + txId);
        } else {
            passToNext(txId, amount);
        }
    }
}

class CEO extends ApprovalHandler {
    @Override
    public void approve(String txId, double amount) {
        System.out.println("[CEO] Approved " + txId + " for $" + amount);
        // CEO handles everything — no passToNext
    }
}

PIECE 3 — Building and using the chain

ApprovalHandler chain = new Teller();
chain.setNext(new Manager())
     .setNext(new Director())
     .setNext(new CEO());

chain.approve("TX001", 500);      // Teller handles it
chain.approve("TX002", 7500);     // Manager handles it
chain.approve("TX003", 60000);    // Director handles it
chain.approve("TX004", 500000);   // CEO handles it

To insert a Regional Manager between Manager and Director:
chain.setNext(new Manager())
     .setNext(new RegionalManager())  // new — no other class changes
     .setNext(new Director())
     .setNext(new CEO());

The chain is assembled in one place. The individual handlers never change.

IMPORTANT — requests can go unhandled:
If you build a chain where no handler covers a certain case, and no handler calls passToNext at the end, the request silently disappears. Always make sure your chain either has a catch-all handler at the end (like CEO above) or explicitly logs unhandled requests.`,
