      id: "mediator",
      name: "Mediator",
      intent: "Define an object that encapsulates how a set of objects interact. Promotes loose coupling by keeping objects from referring to each other explicitly.",
      analogy: "An air traffic control tower. Planes don't talk to each other — they all communicate through the tower. Without it, every pilot would need to track every other plane. The tower centralizes coordination.",
      when: `When you have many objects that communicate with each other, and the communication logic is getting tangled — every object knows about every other object it needs to talk to, creating a web of dependencies.

Here's the concrete problem. A school chat system has Students and Teachers. Without Mediator, each participant holds references to all the others:

class Student {
    private List<Student>  otherStudents;
    private List<Teacher>  teachers;

    public void send(String message) {
        for (Student s : otherStudents) s.receive(message, this);
        for (Teacher t : teachers)      t.receive(message, this);
    }
}

Every Student needs a reference to every other Student and every Teacher. When a new participant type (Admin, Parent) is added, you update every existing class to hold a reference to the new type. When a Student leaves, you update every other participant's list. This is an N × N dependency problem — every pair of participants is directly connected.

Mediator introduces a central hub. Participants only know about the mediator, not each other. The mediator knows about everyone and routes messages. Adding a new participant type means adding it to the mediator — existing participants don't change.`,
      howItWorks: `There are four pieces.

PIECE 1 — The Mediator interface

Declares the communication contract. Participants call sendMessage() on this:

interface ChatMediator {
    void sendMessage(String message, Participant sender);
    void addParticipant(Participant p);
}

PIECE 2 — The Colleague base class

Every participant holds a mediator reference but NOT references to other participants. To send, it calls mediator.sendMessage(). To receive, the mediator calls its receive() method:

abstract class Participant {
    protected ChatMediator mediator; // only knows the mediator
    protected String name;

    public Participant(ChatMediator mediator, String name) {
        this.mediator = mediator;
        this.name     = name;
    }

    public String getName() { return name; }
    public abstract void send(String message);
    public abstract void receive(String message, String from);
}

PIECE 3 — Concrete Mediator

Knows about all participants. Routes messages from sender to everyone else:

class SchoolChatRoom implements ChatMediator {
    private List<Participant> participants = new ArrayList<>();

    @Override
    public void addParticipant(Participant p) {
        participants.add(p);
    }

    @Override
    public void sendMessage(String message, Participant sender) {
        for (Participant p : participants) {
            if (p != sender) { // don't send back to the sender
                p.receive(message, sender.getName());
            }
        }
    }
}

PIECE 4 — Concrete Participants

Student and Teacher only know about the mediator. Zero references to each other:

class Student extends Participant {
    public Student(ChatMediator m, String name) { super(m, name); }

    @Override
    public void send(String message) {
        System.out.println("[Student " + name + " sends]: " + message);
        mediator.sendMessage(message, this); // route through mediator
    }

    @Override
    public void receive(String message, String from) {
        System.out.println("  [Student " + name + " from " + from + "]: " + message);
    }
}

class SchoolTeacher extends Participant {
    public SchoolTeacher(ChatMediator m, String name) { super(m, name); }

    @Override
    public void send(String message) {
        System.out.println("[Teacher " + name + " announces]: " + message);
        mediator.sendMessage(message, this);
    }

    @Override
    public void receive(String message, String from) {
        System.out.println("  [Teacher " + name + " sees from " + from + "]: " + message);
    }
}

Usage:

ChatMediator room = new SchoolChatRoom();
Participant afif  = new Student(room, "Afif");
Participant sadia = new Student(room, "Sadia");
Participant karim = new SchoolTeacher(room, "Mr. Karim");

room.addParticipant(afif);
room.addParticipant(sadia);
room.addParticipant(karim);

afif.send("What's the homework?");
// [Student Afif sends]: What's the homework?
//   [Student Sadia from Afif]: What's the homework?
//   [Teacher Mr. Karim from Afif]: What's the homework?

Adding Admin participant type: write Admin extends Participant, add to room. Zero changes to Student or Teacher.

MEDIATOR vs OBSERVER — they look similar but aren't:
• Observer: one subject notifies many observers (one-to-many, one direction)
• Mediator: many components communicate with many others through a hub (many-to-many, all directions)

If your chat room used Observer, each Student would be a Subject that other Students observe. That brings you back to participants knowing about each other. Mediator keeps the hub as the single point of communication.`,
