      id: "memento",
      name: "Memento",
      intent: "Capture and externalize an object's internal state without violating encapsulation, so it can be restored later.",
      analogy: "A text editor's undo feature. Every time you make a change, the editor silently saves a snapshot. If you hit Ctrl+Z, it restores the last snapshot. The snapshot (memento) is opaque — you can't read or change it directly, only hand it back.",
      when: `When you need to save and restore an object's state — typically for undo/redo — without exposing the object's internal fields to the code doing the saving.

Here's the concrete problem. A teacher edits student scores. You want undo. The naive approach: the caretaker (history manager) reads and writes the score object's fields directly:

class ScoreHistory {
    public void save(StudentScore s) {
        savedScore = s.score;   // reading internal field directly
        savedNotes = s.notes;   // reading internal field directly
    }
    public void restore(StudentScore s) {
        s.score = savedScore;   // writing internal field directly 💥
        s.notes = savedNotes;   // writing internal field directly 💥
    }
}

This breaks encapsulation. ScoreHistory now knows the internal structure of StudentScore. If StudentScore adds a new field or renames one, ScoreHistory breaks. And ScoreHistory has write access to fields that should only be changed through proper methods.

Memento fixes this: StudentScore creates its own snapshots (Memento objects) and restores from them. The caretaker stores the mementos but never reads or modifies their contents — it just holds them and hands them back.`,
      howItWorks: `There are three pieces with specific roles.

PIECE 1 — The Memento (the snapshot)

Stores a captured state. Its fields are not public — only the Originator can read them (using package-private access or an inner class). The Caretaker can hold a Memento but can't peek inside:

class ScoreMemento {
    private final int score;
    private final String notes;

    // Only StudentScore (same package) creates these
    ScoreMemento(int score, String notes) {
        this.score = score;
        this.notes = notes;
    }

    // Package-private getters — only StudentScore can call these
    int    getScore() { return score; }
    String getNotes() { return notes; }
}

package-private (no access modifier) means: only code in the same package can access these. The Caretaker in a different package literally cannot call getScore(). It can only store and return the memento as an opaque object.

PIECE 2 — The Originator (the object being snapshotted)

Creates mementos from its own state. Restores itself from a memento. Only it knows what to put in and how to read it back:

class StudentScore {
    private String studentName;
    private int score;
    private String notes;

    public StudentScore(String name, int score) {
        this.studentName = name;
        this.score = score;
        this.notes = "";
    }

    public void setScore(int score, String notes) {
        this.score = score;
        this.notes = notes;
    }

    // Creates a snapshot of current state
    public ScoreMemento save() {
        return new ScoreMemento(score, notes);
    }

    // Restores state from a snapshot
    public void restore(ScoreMemento m) {
        this.score = m.getScore();
        this.notes = m.getNotes();
        System.out.println(studentName + " → Restored to " + score);
    }
}

PIECE 3 — The Caretaker (manages history)

Stores mementos. Never looks inside them. Just pushes and pops:

class ScoreHistory {
    private Stack<ScoreMemento> history = new Stack<>();

    public void save(ScoreMemento m)  { history.push(m); }
    public ScoreMemento undo()        {
        return history.isEmpty() ? null : history.pop();
    }
}

Usage:

StudentScore score   = new StudentScore("Afif", 70);
ScoreHistory history = new ScoreHistory();

history.save(score.save());          // checkpoint 1: score=70

score.setScore(85, "Re-graded");
history.save(score.save());          // checkpoint 2: score=85

score.setScore(60, "Error found");
System.out.println("Current: 60");

ScoreMemento m = history.undo();    // pop checkpoint 2
if (m != null) score.restore(m);    // back to 85
// → Restored to 85

m = history.undo();                 // pop checkpoint 1
if (m != null) score.restore(m);    // back to 70
// → Restored to 70

MEMENTO vs COMMAND for undo:
• Command undo → reverses the specific action ("put the old value back")
• Memento undo → restores a full object snapshot ("rewind to this earlier moment")

Use Command when you want surgical, action-level undo. Use Memento when the object is complex and you want full rollback to a known good state.`,
