      id: "visitor",
      name: "Visitor",
      intent: "Let you add further operations to objects without modifying them. The visitor 'visits' each element and performs an operation.",
      analogy: "An insurance agent visits buildings. At a residential building, they sell medical insurance. At a bank, theft insurance. At a shop, fire insurance. The buildings don't change — the agent brings the behavior and applies it based on what they visit.",
      when: `When you need to perform multiple distinct, unrelated operations on a set of objects — and you don't want to keep adding new methods to those object classes every time you need a new operation.

Here's the concrete problem. A school has Students, Teachers, and Departments. You need to generate reports — summary report, warning report, PDF export, year-end audit. Without Visitor:

class StudentElement {
    public void printSummary()  { ... } // operation 1
    public void printWarnings() { ... } // operation 2
    public void exportPDF()     { ... } // operation 3
    public void yearEndAudit()  { ... } // operation 4
    // next year: add printHTML(), taxReport(), ...
}

Every new operation adds a new method to StudentElement, TeacherElement, and DepartmentElement. These classes grow forever. A StudentElement should know about students — not about PDF formatting, tax rules, or audit formats.

Visitor says: keep the element classes lean. Move each operation into its own Visitor class. The elements just need one method — accept(visitor) — which lets any visitor come in and do its thing.`,
      howItWorks: `There are four pieces. The accept() method is the key — it's the mechanism that makes everything work.

PIECE 1 — The Visitor interface

One visit method per element type. The visitor knows what to do when it encounters each type:

interface SchoolVisitor {
    void visitStudent(StudentElement s);
    void visitTeacher(TeacherElement t);
    void visitDepartment(DepartmentElement d);
}

PIECE 2 — The Element interface

Just one method: accept(). Every element must implement it:

interface SchoolElement {
    void accept(SchoolVisitor visitor);
}

PIECE 3 — Concrete Elements

Each element implements accept() by calling the right visit method on the visitor — passing itself as the argument. This is called double dispatch:

class StudentElement implements SchoolElement {
    private String name;
    private double gpa;
    private int absences;

    public StudentElement(String name, double gpa, int absences) {
        this.name = name; this.gpa = gpa; this.absences = absences;
    }

    public String getName()  { return name; }
    public double getGpa()   { return gpa; }
    public int getAbsences() { return absences; }

    @Override
    public void accept(SchoolVisitor visitor) {
        visitor.visitStudent(this); // "I'm a Student — call visitStudent"
    }
}

class TeacherElement implements SchoolElement {
    private String name;
    private double rating;

    public TeacherElement(String name, double rating) {
        this.name = name; this.rating = rating;
    }

    public String getName()   { return name; }
    public double getRating() { return rating; }

    @Override
    public void accept(SchoolVisitor visitor) {
        visitor.visitTeacher(this); // "I'm a Teacher — call visitTeacher"
    }
}

PIECE 4 — Concrete Visitors

Each visitor is one complete operation. It handles every element type:

class SummaryReportVisitor implements SchoolVisitor {
    @Override
    public void visitStudent(StudentElement s) {
        System.out.printf("[STUDENT] %-12s GPA: %.1f  Absences: %d%n",
            s.getName(), s.getGpa(), s.getAbsences());
    }
    @Override
    public void visitTeacher(TeacherElement t) {
        System.out.printf("[TEACHER] %-12s Rating: %.1f%n",
            t.getName(), t.getRating());
    }
    @Override
    public void visitDepartment(DepartmentElement d) { ... }
}

class WarningReportVisitor implements SchoolVisitor {
    @Override
    public void visitStudent(StudentElement s) {
        if (s.getAbsences() > 5)
            System.out.println("[WARNING] " + s.getName() + " has too many absences!");
        if (s.getGpa() < 2.5)
            System.out.println("[WARNING] " + s.getName() + " has low GPA!");
    }
    @Override
    public void visitTeacher(TeacherElement t) {
        if (t.getRating() < 3.0)
            System.out.println("[WARNING] " + t.getName() + " has low rating!");
    }
    @Override
    public void visitDepartment(DepartmentElement d) { ... }
}

Usage:

SchoolElement[] elements = {
    new StudentElement("Afif",  3.8, 2),
    new StudentElement("Sadia", 2.1, 8),
    new TeacherElement("Mr. Karim", 4.5),
    new TeacherElement("Ms. Rina",  2.7),
};

SchoolVisitor summary  = new SummaryReportVisitor();
SchoolVisitor warnings = new WarningReportVisitor();

for (SchoolElement e : elements) e.accept(summary);
for (SchoolElement e : elements) e.accept(warnings);

WHY double dispatch?
Normal method calls dispatch on one type — the object's type. Here we need dispatch on two types: what kind of element is this AND what operation are we doing? 

e.accept(visitor)         → dispatches on e's type (Student? Teacher?)
visitor.visitStudent(this) → dispatches on visitor's type (Summary? Warning?)

Two dispatch steps = double dispatch. This is what makes the right visit method get called for the right combination.

THE ONE TRADEOFF:
Adding a new Visitor (new operation) = easy, one new class.
Adding a new Element type = hard, must update every existing Visitor. This is the inverse of the Open/Closed problem that Visitor solves.`,
